Section 1:
1 L.D. 61
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
3 LABOR
5 STATE OF MAINE
6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 25, L.D. 61, “An Act to Regulate
10 Employer Surveillance to Protect Workers”
11 Amend the bill in section 1 in sub-c. 1-E in §620-A in subsection 1 by inserting after
12 paragraph C the following:
13 'D. "Personal care services" means services provided by a licensed personal care
14 agency and includes, but is not limited to, services related to activities of daily living,
15 household tasks and medication reminders.'
16 Amend the bill in section 1 in sub-c. 1-E in §620-A in subsection 3 in the last line (page
17 1, line 23 in L.D.) by inserting after the following: "surveillance" the following: 'unless the
18 audiovisual monitoring is required by the employer for duties of the job'
19 Amend the bill in section 1 in sub-c. 1-E in §620-A in subsection 5 in the last line (page
20 1, line 29 in L.D.) by inserting after the following: "surveillance" the following: ', and the
21 employer shall provide written notice at least once per calendar year to all current
22 employees that the employer engages in employer surveillance'
23 Amend the bill in section 1 in sub-c. 1-E in §620-A by striking out all of subsection 6
24 (page 1, lines 30 to 32 in L.D.).
25 Amend the bill in section 1 in sub-c. 1-E in §620-A by inserting after subsection 6 the
26 following:
27 '7. Personal care services settings; applicability. This section does not apply to
28 employer surveillance that has been installed or caused to be installed by an employer,
29 patient, client or unpaid caregiver in a setting in which personal care services are expected
30 to be provided by an employee.
31 8. Penalties; enforcement. An employer that violates this section is subject to a fine
32 of not less than $100 and not more than $500 for each violation. The Department of Labor
33 shall enforce this section within existing resources using strategic enforcement.'
Page 1 - 132LR0107(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 25, L.D. 61
1 Amend the bill in section 1 in sub-c. 1-E in §620-A in subsection 7 in the first line
2 (page 1, line 33 in L.D.) by striking out the following: "shall" and inserting the following:
3 'may'
4 Amend the bill in section 1 in sub-c. 1-E in §620-A by renumbering the subsections to
5 read consecutively.
6 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
7 number to read consecutively.
8 SUMMARY
99 This amendment, which is the majority report of the committee, amends the bill by
1100 providing an exemption from the audiovisual monitoring restriction for employers who
1111 require audiovisual monitoring in the employee's residence or personal vehicle or on the
1122 employee's property for duties of the job. The amendment provides an exemption for the
1133 use of surveillance in personal care services settings. The amendment also requires that a
1144 written notice that the employer engages in employer surveillance is given to current
1155 employees at least once per calendar year and removes the private right of action provision
1166 from the bill.
1177 FISCAL NOTE REQUIRED
1188 (See attached)
Page 2 - 132LR0107(02)
